WEBVTT

00:00:00.400 --> 00:00:04.420
PyAnalySeries provides a simple and efficient way to smooth time

00:00:04.420 --> 00:00:05.350
series data.

00:00:06.540 --> 00:00:10.600
Filtering is applied in the X-domain, using a centered moving

00:00:10.600 --> 00:00:13.760
average based on a convolution with a square window.

00:00:14.970 --> 00:00:17.850
Each value is replaced by the average of its neighboring

00:00:17.850 --> 00:00:18.510
points.

00:00:19.610 --> 00:00:24.020
This reduces high-frequency variability while preserving the main trends of

00:00:24.020 --> 00:00:24.750
the signal.

00:00:26.130 --> 00:00:29.580
Other X-domain filtering methods could be implemented if needed.

00:00:30.620 --> 00:00:32.900
Let’s return to our practical example.

00:00:34.070 --> 00:00:37.290
The “ PercAndes ” record remains slightly noisy, even after

00:00:37.290 --> 00:00:38.420
resampling at 0.

00:00:38.420 --> 00:00:40.060
2 5 thousand years.

00:00:41.320 --> 00:00:45.260
We therefore apply a smoothing average to improve readability.

00:00:46.590 --> 00:00:50.390
Select the record, then go to Process and choose “

00:00:50.390 --> 00:00:52.290
Define Smoothing Average ”.

00:00:53.390 --> 00:00:56.330
You can test different window sizes depending on the level

00:00:56.330 --> 00:00:57.670
of smoothing required.

00:00:59.070 --> 00:01:02.380
Here, we use a 5-point running average.

00:01:02.380 --> 00:01:03.190
Given the 0.

00:01:03.190 --> 00:01:07.100
2 5 thousand years sampling, this corresponds to a smoothing

00:01:07.100 --> 00:01:08.860
window of 1 thousand years.

00:01:10.450 --> 00:01:15.230
Most of the high-frequency variability is effectively removed, while preserving

00:01:15.230 --> 00:01:16.850
the main trends of the signal.

00:01:18.130 --> 00:01:21.100
You can then save the filtered series and the filter

00:01:21.100 --> 00:01:23.800
for later reuse on other series.

00:01:26.080 --> 00:01:28.900
You can also hover over the item ID to display

00:01:28.900 --> 00:01:29.910
its history.
